#Text=PART II
#Text=“ She never even asked who it was , ” Amelia reported to her sisters , when she had returned to the house .
#Text=“ Because she knew , ” replied Sophia , sagely ;
#Text=“ there has never been any old friend but that one old friend to come back into Eudora Yates ’s life . ”
#Text=“ Has he come back into her life , I wonder ? ” said Amelia .
#Text=“ What did he return to Wellwood for if he did n’t come for that ?
#Text=All his relatives are gone .
#Text=He never married .
#Text=Yes , he has come back to see Eudora and marry her , if she will have him .
#Text=No man who ever loved Eudora would ever get over loving her .
#Text=And he will not be shocked when he sees her .
#Text=She is no more changed than a beautiful old statue . ”
#Text=“ HE is changed , though , ” said Amelia .
#Text=“ I saw him the other day .
#Text=He did n’t see me , and I would hardly have known him .
#Text=He has grown stout , and his hair is gray . ”
#Text=“ Eudora ’s hair is gray , ” said Sophia .
#Text=“ Yes , but you can see the gold through Eudora ’s gray .
#Text=It just looks as if a shadow was thrown over it .
#Text=It does n’t change her .
#Text=Harry Lawton ’s gray hair does change him . ”
#Text=“ If , ” said Anna , sentimentally , “ Eudora thinks Harry ’s hair turned gray for love of her , you can trust her or any woman to see the gold through it . ”
#Text=“ Harry ’s hair was never gold -- just an ordinary brown , ” said Amelia .
#Text=“ Anyway , the Lawtons turned gray young . ”
#Text=“ She wo n’t think of that at all , ” said Sophia .
#Text=“ I wonder why Eudora always avoided him so , years ago , ” said Amelia .
#Text=“ Why does n’t a girl in a field of daisies stop to pick one , which she never forgets ? ” said Sophia .
#Text=“ Eudora had so many chances , and I do n’t think her heart was fixed when she was very young ; at least , I do n’t think it was fixed so she knew it . ”
#Text=“ I wonder , ” said Amelia , “ if he will go and call on her . ”
#Text=Amelia privately wished that she lived near enough to know if Harry Lawton did call .

#Text=She , as well as Mrs. Joseph Glynn , would have enjoyed watching out and knowing something of the village happenings , but the Lancaster house was situated so far from the road , behind its grove of trees , that nothing whatever could be seen .
#Text=“ I doubt if Eudora tells , if he does call -- that is , not unless something definite happens , ” said Anna .
#Text=“ No , ” remarked Amelia , sadly .
#Text=“ Eudora is a dear , but she is very silent with regard to her own affairs . ”
#Text=“ She ought to be , ” said Sophia , with her married authority .
#Text=She was , to her sisters , as one who had passed within the shrine and was dignifiedly silent with regard to its intimate mysteries .
#Text=“ I suppose so , ” assented Anna , with a soft sigh .
#Text=Amelia sighed also .
#Text=Then she took the tea-tray out of the room .
#Text=She had to make some biscuits for supper .
#Text=Meantime Eudora was pacing homeward with the baby-carriage .
#Text=Her serene face was a little perturbed .
#Text=Her oval cheeks were flushed , and her mouth now and then trembled .

#Text=She had , if she followed her usual course , to pass the Wellwood Inn , but she could diverge , and by taking a side street and walking a half-mile farther reach home without coming in sight of the inn .
#Text=She did so to-day .
#Text=When she reached the side street she turned rather swiftly and gave a little sigh of relief .
#Text=She was afraid that she might meet Harry Lawton .
#Text=It was a lonely way .
#Text=There was a brook on one side , bordered thickly with bushy willows which were turning gold-green .
#Text=On the other side were undulating pasture-lands on which grazed a few sheep .
#Text=There were no houses until she reached the turn which would lead back to the main street , on which her home was located .
#Text=Eudora was about midway of this street when she saw a man approaching .
#Text=He was a large man clad in gray , and he was swinging an umbrella .
#Text=Somehow the swing of that umbrella , even from a distance , gave an impression of embarrassment and boyish hesitation .
#Text=Eudora did not know him at first .
#Text=She had expected to see the same Harry Lawton who had gone away .
#Text=She did not expect to see a stout , middle-aged man , but a slim youth .
#Text=However , as they drew nearer each other , she knew ; and curiously enough it was that swing of the tightly furled umbrella which gave her the clue .
#Text=She knew Harry because of that .
#Text=It was a little boyish trick which had survived time .

#Text=It was too late for her to draw back , for he had seen her , and Eudora was keenly alive to the indignity of abruptly turning and scuttling away with the tail of her black silk swishing , her India shawl trailing , and the baby-carriage bumping over the furrows .
#Text=She continued , and Harry Lawton continued , and they met .
#Text=Harry Lawton had known Eudora at once .
#Text=She looked the same to him as when she had been a girl , and he looked the same to her when he spoke .
#Text=“ Hullo , Eudora , ” said Harry Lawton , in a ludicrously boyish fashion .
#Text=His face flushed , too , like a boy .
#Text=He extended his hand like a boy .
#Text=The man , seen near at hand , was a boy .
#Text=In reality he himself had not changed .
#Text=A few layers of flesh and a change of color-cells do not make another man .
#Text=He had always been a simple , sincere , friendly soul , beloved of men and women alike , and he was that now .
#Text=Eudora held out her hand , and her eyes fell before the eyes of the man , in an absurd fashion for such a stately creature as she .
#Text=But the man himself acted like a great happy overgrown school-boy .
